  {
    "id": "a7f4d87a-dd18-48a8-9221-c6c24e300a1a",
    "sentence": "So I'm afraid to tell you that those are all great questions, and they're questions that the Committee is just turning to now. So we had -- we had a discussion, as you know, at the last meeting, an introductory discussion of the balance sheet and a teeing up of the issues.",
    "source": "FOMCpresconf20220126.json",
    "doc_type": "press_conference_qa",
    "date": "20220126",
    "context_question": "Good afternoon, Chair Powell. Nick Timiraos of the Wall Street Journal. I, I have a couple of questions on the balance sheet. The statement on the balance sheet today calls for “significantly reducing” your holdings. What does that mean? And then, apart from moving sooner and faster to shrink the holdings, are there any other ways in which you and your colleagues are seriously thinking about recalibrating this process? And, finally, how much disagreement is there around how you should use this tool, including active sales rather than passive sales or changes in the composition of reinvestments? Thank you.",
