  {
    "id": "ace9d73d-c6a7-46ec-9681-a177bb3047e8",
    "sentence": "You couched it in terms of real rates.",
    "source": "FOMCpresconf20220316.json",
    "doc_type": "press_conference_qa",
    "date": "20220316",
    "context_question": "Nick Timiraos of the Wall Street Journal. Chair Powell, over the last six months, the Fed has shifted its policy stance quite a bit. Six months ago, you were still buying assets. Most officials weren’t projecting any interest rate increases this year. And yet, despite the shift over the last six months, real rates are as negative today as they were then. So how concerned are you that further inflation surprises will offset the effects of recent policy firming by leading real rates to stay at levels that do not actually provide much restraint to the economy? Thanks.",
    "top": "",
    "ten": "",
    "sen": "",
    "dir": "",
    "com": "",
    "hor": "",
    "con": "",
    "dom": "",
    "ris": "",
    "wid": ""
